Schedule Updates for Football and Cross Country

Tomorrow's XC meet at Anamosa has been CANCELLED due to wet conditions. They received too much rain over night to make it possible to run tomorrow.

Tonights JV game has been PPD at this point. Plans are in the works to try and make it work Monday. More details later today or this weekend in regards to the JV game.

Tonights Varsity game at Winthrop is still on. They will be conducting their Homecoming activities at 6:15 PM and we are planning to start the Varsity game between 6:45 PM and 7:00 PM. You won't miss any of the game if you are there at 6:45. They are not sure how long the Homecoming activities will take because it is not what they normally due. Just like us, they are trying to make things work with lots of changing factors.

I hope to see everyone in Winthrop tonight. Stay dry! I will post information if the game is going to be broadcasted in any way but at this point there is no LiveStream or Radio tonight.

Go Cats!

post_text:
Fall activities are here!

The first game action for any of our teams is the football team, this Friday at MFL, Mar-Mac. JV starts at 5:00, Varsity to follow!

HS Volleyball kicks off their season on Tuesday Sept. 1st at Clayton Ridge.

XC starts their season at Luana (Tri-City Golf Course) on Thursday Sept. 3rd.

Fall Play begins auditions this week. Good luck to those going after those roles.

The Band Man Mr. Ford is getting the Marching Band ready to perform at the first home game on Sept. 4th and will have a NEW location during home games to play. Should create a cool atmosphere for everyone in attendance.

Coach Teymer and the Dance Team (14 Dancers) are practicing their routines and will be performing at home football games as well.

JH FB kicks off their season at home on Thursday Sept. 10th against East Buch and that same night JH VB starts their season at home against Springville.

The Fall season is a busy time but we wouldn't want it any other way.

Good luck & stay healthy!

Go Cats!

Guidelines for home events. Please expect to follow these guidelines at any home event.

-Indoor event seating will be clearly marked with tape as to where you can/can't sit.

-Outdoor seating areas at the football field are being expanded. The band will now be located in the west end zone which opens up more bleacher seating for the fans to spread out.

-The east end zone will now be available for fans to sit on blankets on the grass or track area. Lawn chairs will be allowed on the grass areas inside the fence on the east end.

We are trying to provide the safest possible environment under the current situation to help keep our student-athletes, coaches, managers, officials, game workers, fans as well as opposing players, coaches and fans as healthy as we can while competing and attending events.

If you have any questions about these guidelines, please send them to Trevor Arnold, AD (trevorarnold@maquoketa-v.k12.ia.us)

post_text:
Attention all Fall athlete parents-HS & JH cross country, HS & JH football, HS & JH volleyball & Dance

Tomorrow, Saturday, August 22, at 10am we will be opening up a schedule for the concession stand for fall athletic events for you to sign up for a date/time that works for you. We are asking that each family takes at least 2 spots, many of you have multiple athletes participating and are encouraged to sign up for more than 2 spots. We will be leaving this open until the end of Friday, August 28th, if you have not signed up by then you will be assigned shifts.

Please keep in mind that you are able to sign up for any spot, i.e. a HS football family could sign up for a JH football game or volleyball match, a volleyball family could sign up for a football game, etc. And as always, any other volunteers will be welcomed!

Reach out to the Athletic Boosters if you have any questions.

Go Cats!

Attention JH Football Parents/Guardians

Parents / Guardians,
I hope this quick reminder finds you all well. I just wanted to gently remind everyone that we will be handing out equipment for junior high football this week.
Wednesday, Aug. 19 @ 5:30 PM - 8th Grade
Thursday, Aug. 20 @ 5:30 PM - 7th Grade
We hope this does not take real long, but due to social distancing we will have to limit the number of athletes working through the process at one time.
If you have not turned in all of the paperwork, please bring them completed at that time.
Also, please refer to the calendar that was distributed at the parent meeting after camp. The first practice will be the first day of school, Aug. 24 from 5:30-7 PM. We will also practice at that same time on Tuesday, August 25.

Thank you
Coach Huegel

post_text: Due to the current situation, we have made the decision to switch the productions of our fall musical and spring play. This year we will have a fall play and a spring musical. Our number one priority is to safely give our students as many opportunities as possible for stage productions. With the latest studies and data in regards to singing on stage, we truly feel this gives our performers the best chance at two shows. The fall play will take place the first weekend in November and the spring musical will take place the second weekend in May. Exact dates and times are still being determined. Thank you.

post_text:
Important information regarding sports physicals. This information comes directly from the IHSAA/IGHSAU.

Pre-Participation Physicals

A reminder that the following amendment was issued by Governor Reynolds on June 25:

Sec. 49. SCHOOL PHYSICALS â€”â€” TEMPORARY PROVISIONS. For the period beginning on the effective date of this division of this Act through December 31, 2020, a student participating in interscholastic athletics who presents to the studentâ€™s superintendent a certificate signed on or after July 1, 2019, by a licensed physician or surgeon, osteopathic physician or surgeon, chiropractor, physician assistant, or advanced registered nurse practitioner, to the effect that the student has been examined and may safely engage in athletic competition, shall be deemed to have complied with the regulatory provisions of 281 IAC36.14(1).

The short version is that all physicals signed on or after July 1, 2019 are good through December of 2020.

post_text: The Foundation for the Future of Delaware County Covid-19 Relief Fund has partnered with Iowa State Extension and Outreach to create Kits for Kids activity bags. These free kits have a variety of activities and supplies for students in Grades K-5. Four different themes of kits are available: Art, STEM, Fizz, Bubble & Goo, and Staycation. Kits for Kids will be distributed on Monday, June 29, beginning at 11:00 at the lunch pick-up sites in Delhi, Earlville, and Hopkinton while supplies last. Families who do not usually pick up lunches can still stop by any distribution site to pick up a Kits for Kids activity bag. Due to the limited number of kits available, we recommend one kit per family as many of the activities and supplies can be reused by multiple family members. We hope your child will enjoy these activities and we want to thank ISU Extension and Outreach for their help in creating and packing the Kits for Kids activities!

post_text:
Tee Ball starts tonight at 5:30 PM.

With social distancing guidelines we want to help make sure we adhere to those guidelines as well as provide a great view to watch your little leaguer play.

This is hopefully going to help from having too many people congregating around the dugout areas.

As a reminder, the dugout and extended dugout areas are for players and coaches only which includes the set of bleachers directly behind home plate.

Please refrain from grouping up in this area behind home plate. The best case scenario is to have all parents/fans watch from beyond the dugouts and down each of the foul line outside the fence along with using the designated mowed line in the outfield. This is probably the best place to go and get a great view of the field.

See you at the field!

When the pandemic hit, many extra-curricular activities were cut short or greatly altered, including Maquoketa Valley High School's spring play. When they were unable to perform their original production, which was already cast, the directors and students jumped at the opportunity to perform another show specifically designed for the virtual world. The students rehearsed with the directors virtually twice a week. Thank you to directors Debbie DeVore and Jennifer Teymer, as well as all of the cast members, for their flexibility, dedication, and creativity! Please share this post or link with your friends and family members. Without further adieu, Maquoketa Valley High School proudly presents, "Stranded: Views from Quarantine."

Varsity Baseball dates are all included. New this year to Tri-Rivers Baseball schedules is the V/JV Crossover games. The first game on those nights is the Varsity game and will be counted as a conference game. The second game is considered a JV game and will not count towards conference records.

More information will be coming for coaches, players and fans this week in regards to the guidelines we will be following at our facilities, on the road and during the games/practices.

Go Cats!

DMACC will be offering zoom sessions this month for students/parents. Click the link to register. Sessions will be one of the following formats:

Career Presentations: Industry professionals share their own unique career pathways; may be a single presenter or a panel. (30 minutes)

Informal Interviews: PPS staff (teachers, career coordinators, CTE office team) will interview professionals about their career and career path. (30 minutes)

Teaching a Skill or Demo : Industry professionals will teach a skill or lead a demonstration to students using online resources, video and applied ins truction. (30 minutes)

Professional Skills Presentations: Industry professionals will lead workshops focused on work readiness/professional skills, resume writing and review, etc. (30 minutes)

post_text:
Good Morning:
We held a virtual meeting with senior students and parents last night. We have finalized plans for graduation and prom.

Here are the dates:
Prom: Saturday June 6th @ Delhi Legion (Grand March @ park prior to Dance from 8-11 pm).
Graduation: Sunday June 7th @ 4:00 pm

If the guidelines have not been lifted for these 2 June dates, we will plan for these dates:
Prom: Friday July 3rd @ Delhi Legion (Grand March @ park prior to Dance from 8-11 pm).
Graduation: Sunday July 5th @ 4:00 pm

If the guidelines still have not been lifted by July 3rd, prom will be cancelled and we will proceed with a graduation ceremony on July 5th. We discussed doing a car parade for graduation on July 5th if the social distancing guidelines have not been lifted.

Hope everyone is doing well. Take care.

Parents/Families,

The IHSAA and IGHSAU have implemented a Family Week that will go into effect next Summer. From the date of Saturday July 25th 2021 to August 1st 2021 there will be no individual, group or team workouts allowed for any state sponsored activities. This would include all sports for grades 7-12.

Something of this nature was already planned for this summer here at MV but due to our current situation, those restrictions will not be placed on our athletes & coaches. If we are allowed to get back to working with the kids, I think we are all going to be pretty excited to do that and not need another break since we are currently on a longer break than we even want.

I wanted to share this information so if you happen to be doing some long-term vacation planning, July 25th-August 1st 2021 might be the ideal time for your family and student-athlete(s) to get away before Fall Camps begin.

Please let me know if you have any questions regarding this.

Trevor Arnold, Activities Director

post_text: Congratulations to the Maquoketa Valley Individual Events Contest Speech Team! When they found out state speech was canceled, they stepped up 24 hours later and performed for judges at a mini-contest hosted at home. We ended up with 38 overall I ratings and 5 overall II ratings. The following students were nominated for All-State: Mason Lubben in Acting and Public Address, Lydia Helle in Expository Address, Shelby March in After Dinner Speaking, Paige Panosh in Spontaneous Speaking, Andrew Kloser in Storytelling, Carlie Lewin in Reviewing, Preston Roling in Radio News Announcing, Kylie Chesnut in Storytelling, and McKenna Thompson in Storytelling. Thank you to each and every student for their hard work, dedication, flexibility, and professionalism all season long! We are extremely proud of ALL of our performers.

post_text: What an amazing day! First and foremost, THANK YOU to every single person who took time out of their busy schedule to help make our district IE speech contest run smoothly. We heard many compliments and this is because of YOU! A huge shout-out to the Maquoketa Valley Fine Arts Booster Club, and all of their members, for the extra hours spent behind-the-scenes. Your continued support and dedication is extremely appreciated. The MV Wildcats had an incredible day! In grades 10-12, we received 36 division one ratings and 6 division two ratings. For grade 9, all 7 performances received a division one rating. Students with a division one rating advance to the state contest at Starmont High School on Saturday, March 14. Again, thank you to everyone. We love you and are blessed to be a part of such a caring and supportive district. Act Proud, Speak Loud, Dream BIG!

post_text: To say that we work in an incredible school district with awesome students, amazing family members, supportive community members, and dedicated staff, faculty, administration, and school board, is an insanely huge understatement! For six hours on Monday, the aforementioned groups worked together as a well-oiled machine hosting the Tri-Rivers Conference IE Speech Contest. We could NOT do what we do without ALL of you! Maquoketa Valley earned the conference championship with 185 points. Of the 22 Best-of-Center Awards given out, the Wildcats earned 13. Overall ratings included 34 one ratings and 5 two ratings for grades 10-12 and 5 one ratings and 2 two ratings for grade 9. THANK YOU from the bottom of our hearts for your hard work and support. The best part is that we get to do it all over again on Saturday!!

post_text: Congratulations to the MV Contest Speech Team on a great day! Fifteen events received a division I rating and will advance to state competition at Dubuque Senior on Saturday, February 8. Those groups earning a I include all three group improvisations, RICH and THN radio broadcastings, the one-act play, all three ensemble actings, both the 9th grade and grades 10-12 readers theatres, the musical theatre, the "Iowa Unsolved" tv news, grades 10-12 choral reading, and the "Sweet Tooth" group mime. Events receiving a division II rating today include both short films, BEAT radio broadcasting, the solo mime, the 9th grade choral reading, "DBD" tv news, and the "Not All Heroes Wear Capes" group mime. We are extremely proud of all of our students!
